# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-anonymization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] In the context of medical data, anonymized data refers to data from which the patient cannot be identified by the recipient of the information.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] The name, address, and full postcode must be removed, together with any other information which, in conjunction with other data held by or disclosed to the recipient, could identify the patient.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] There will always be a risk that anonymized data may not stay anonymous over time.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Pairing the anonymized dataset with other data, clever techniques and raw power are some of the ways previously anonymous data sets have become de-anonymized; The data subjects are no longer anonymous.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] De-anonymization is the reverse process in which anonymous data is cross-referenced with other data sources to re-identify the anonymous data source.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Generalization and perturbation are the two popular anonymization approaches for relational data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] The process of obscuring data with the ability to re-identify it later is also called pseudonymization and is one way companies can store data in a way that is HIPAA compliant.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] However, according to ARTICLE 29 DATA PROTECTION WORKING PARTY, Directive 95/46/EC refers to anonymisation in Recital 26 "signifies that to anonymise any data, the data must be stripped of sufficient elements such that the data subject can no longer be identified.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] More precisely, that data must be processed in such a way that it can no longer be used to identify a natural person by using “all the means likely reasonably to be used” by either the controller or a third party.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] An important factor is that the processing must be irreversible.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] The Directive does not clarify how such a de-identification process should or could be performed.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] The focus is on the outcome: that data should be such as not to allow the data subject to be identified via “all” “likely” and “reasonable” means.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Reference is made to codes of conduct as a tool to set out possible anonymisation mechanisms as well as retention in a form in which identification of the data subject is “no longer possible”.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] There are five types of data anonymization operations: generalization, suppression, anatomization, permutation, and perturbation.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] The European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) requires that stored data on people in the EU undergo either anonymization or a pseudonymization process.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] According to the EDPS and AEPD, no one, including the data controller, should be able to re-identify data subjects in a properly anonymized dataset.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Research by data scientists at Imperial College in London and UCLouvain in Belgium, as well as a ruling by Judge Michal Agmon-Gonen of the Tel Aviv District Court, highlight the shortcomings of "Anonymisation" in today's big data world.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Anonymisation reflects an outdated approach to data protection that was developed when the processing of data was limited to isolated (siloed) applications, prior to the popularity of big data processing involving the widespread sharing and combining of data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Removing identifying metadata from computer files is important for anonymizing them.
[src:data-anonymization/data-anonymization] Metadata removal tools are useful for achieving this.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The main reason to mask data is to protect information that is classified as personally identifiable information, or mission critical data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] However, the data must remain usable for the purposes of undertaking valid test cycles.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It must also look real and appear consistent.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is more common to have masking applied to data that is represented outside of a corporate production system.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In other words, where data is needed for the purpose of application development, building program extensions and conducting various test cycles.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is common practice in enterprise computing to take data from the production systems to fill the data component, required for these non-production environments.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] However, this practice is not always restricted to non-production environments.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In some organizations, data that appears on terminal screens to call center operators may have masking dynamically applied based on user security permissions (e.g. preventing call center operators from viewing credit card numbers in billing systems).
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The primary concern from a corporate governance perspective is that personnel conducting work in these non-production environments are not always security cleared to operate with the information contained in the production data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This practice represents a security hole where data can be copied by unauthorized personnel, and security measures associated with standard production level controls can be easily bypassed.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This represents an access point for a data security breach.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The data must undergo enough changes so that it is not obvious that the masked data is from a source of production data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] For example, it may be common knowledge in an organisation that there are 10 senior managers all earning in excess of $300k.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] If a test environment of the organisation's HR System also includes 10 identities in the same earning-bracket, then other information could be pieced together to reverse-engineer a real-life identity.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Theoretically, if the data is obviously masked or obfuscated, then it would be reasonable for someone intending a data breach to assume that they could reverse engineer identity-data if they had some degree of knowledge of the identities in the production data-set.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Accordingly, data obfuscation or masking of a data-set applies in such a manner as to ensure that identity and sensitive data records are protected - not just the individual data elements in discrete fields and tables.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The masked values may be required to be consistent across multiple databases within an organization when the databases each contain the specific data element being masked.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Additional constraints as mentioned in (1) above may also apply depending on the data element(s) involved.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Where different character sets are used across the databases that need to connect in this scenario, a scheme of converting the original values to a common representation will need to be applied, either by the masking algorithm itself or prior to invoking said algorithm.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Substitution is one of the most effective methods of applying data masking and being able to preserve the authentic look and feel of the data records.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It allows the masking to be performed in such a manner that another authentic-looking value can be substituted for the existing value.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] There are several data field types where this approach provides optimal benefit in disguising the overall data subset as to whether or not it is a masked data set.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] For example, if dealing with source data which contains customer records, real life surname or first name can be randomly substituted from a supplied or customised look up file.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In most cases, the substitution files will need to be fairly extensive so having large substitution datasets as well the ability to apply customized data substitution sets should be a key element of the evaluation criteria for any data masking solution.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The shuffling method is a very common form of data obfuscation.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is similar to the substitution method but it derives the substitution set from the same column of data that is being masked.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In very simple terms, the data is randomly shuffled within the column.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] However, if used in isolation, anyone with any knowledge of the original data can then apply a "what if" scenario to the data set and then piece back together a real identity.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The shuffling method is also open to being reversed if the shuffling algorithm can be deciphered.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Data shuffling overcomes reservations about using perturbed or modified confidential data because it retains all the desirable properties of perturbation while performing better than other masking techniques in both data utility and disclosure risk.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Shuffling, however, has some real strengths in certain areas.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] If for instance, the end of year figures for financial information in a test data base, one can mask the names of the suppliers and then shuffle the value of the accounts throughout the masked database.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is highly unlikely that anyone, even someone with intimate knowledge of the original data could derive a true data record back to its original values.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The numeric variance method is very useful for applying to financial and date driven information fields.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Effectively, a method utilising this manner of masking can still leave a meaningful range in a financial data set such as payroll.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] If the variance applied is around +/- 10% then it is still a very meaningful data set in terms of the ranges of salaries that are paid to the recipients.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The same also applies to the date information.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Encryption is often the most complex approach to solving the data masking problem.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The encryption algorithm often requires that a "key" be applied to view the data based on user rights.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This often sounds like the best solution, but in practice the key may then be given out to personnel without the proper rights to view the data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This then defeats the purpose of the masking exercise.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Old databases may then get copied with the original credentials of the supplied key and the same uncontrolled problem lives on.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Recently, the problem of encrypting data while preserving the properties of the entities got recognition and a newly acquired interest among the vendors and academia.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] New challenge gave birth to algorithms performing format-preserving encryption.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] These are based on the accepted Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithmic mode recognized by NIST.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Sometimes a very simplistic approach to masking is adopted through applying a null value to a particular field.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The null value approach is really only useful to prevent visibility of the data element.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In almost all cases, it lessens the degree of data integrity that is maintained in the masked data set.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is not a realistic value and will then fail any application logic validation that may have been applied in the front end software that is in the system under test.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It also highlights to anyone that wishes to reverse engineer any of the identity data that data masking has been applied to some degree on the data set.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Character scrambling or masking out of certain fields is also another simplistic yet very effective method of preventing sensitive information to be viewed.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is really an extension of the previous method of nulling out, but there is a greater emphasis on keeping the data real and not fully masked all together.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This is commonly applied to credit card data in production systems.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] For instance, an operator at a call centre might bill an item to a customer's credit card.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] They then quote a billing reference to the card with the last 4 digits of XXXX XXXX xxxx 6789.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] As an operator they can only see the last 4 digits of the card number, but once the billing system passes the customer's details for charging, the full number is revealed to the payment gateway systems.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This system is not very effective for test systems, but it is very useful for the billing scenario detailed above.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] It is also commonly known as a dynamic data masking method.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Additional rules can also be factored into any masking solution regardless of how the masking methods are constructed.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Product agnostic white papers are a good source of information for exploring some of the more common complex requirements for enterprise masking solutions, which include row internal synchronization rules, table internal synchronization rules and table to Table Synchronization Rules.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Data masking is tightly coupled with building test data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Two major types of data masking are static and on-the-fly data masking.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Static data masking is usually performed on the golden copy of the database, but can also be applied to values in other sources, including files.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Deterministic masking is the process of replacing a value in a column with the same value whether in the same row, the same table, the same database/schema and between instances/servers/database types.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Example: A database has multiple tables, each with a column that has first names.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] With deterministic masking the first name will always be replaced with the same value – “Lynne” will always become “Denise” – wherever “Lynne” may be in the database.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] There are also alternatives to the static data masking that rely on stochastic perturbations of the data that preserve some of the statistical properties of the original data.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Examples of statistical data obfuscation methods include differential privacy and the *DataSifter* method.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] On-the-fly data masking happens in the process of transferring data from environment to environment without data touching the disk on its way.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The same technique is applied to "Dynamic Data Masking" but one record at a time.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This type of data masking is most useful for environments that do continuous deployments as well as for heavily integrated applications.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Organizations that employ continuous deployment or continuous delivery practices do not have the time necessary to create a backup and load it to the golden copy of the database.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Thus, continuously sending smaller subsets (deltas) of masked testing data from production is important.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In heavily integrated applications, developers get feeds from other production systems at the very onset of development and masking of these feeds is either overlooked and not budgeted until later, making organizations non-compliant.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Having on-the-fly data masking in place becomes essential.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is similar to on-the-fly data masking, but it differs in the sense that on-the-fly data masking is about copying data from one source to another source so that the latter can be shared.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Dynamic data masking happens at runtime, dynamically, and on-demand so that there doesn't need to be a second data source where to store the masked data dynamically.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Dynamic data masking enables several scenarios, many of which revolve around strict privacy regulations e.g. the Singapore Monetary Authority or the Privacy regulations in Europe.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is attribute-based and policy-driven.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Dynamic data masking can also be used to encrypt or decrypt values on the fly especially when using format-preserving encryption.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Several standards have emerged in recent years to implement dynamic data filtering and masking.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] For instance, XACML policies can be used to mask data inside databases.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Network proxy between the application and the database: Captures the SQL and applies rewrite on the select request.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Database proxy: is a variation of network proxy.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Database proxy is deployed usually between applications/users and the database.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Applications and users are connecting to the database through database security proxy.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] There are no changes to the way applications and users are connecting to the database.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] There is also no need of an agent to be installed on the database server.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The sql queries are rewritten, but when implemented, this type of dynamic data masking also supported within store procedures and database functions.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Network proxy between the end-user and the application: identifying text strings and replacing them.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This method is not applicable for complex applications as it will easily cause corruption when the real-time string replacement is unintentionally applied.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Code changes in the applications & XACML: code changes are usually hard to perform, impossible to maintain and not applicable for packaged applications.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Within the application run-time: By instrumenting the application run-time, policies are defined to rewrite the result set returned from the data sources, while having full visibility to the application user.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This method is the only applicable way to dynamically mask complex applications as it enables control to the data request, data result and user result.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Supported by a browser plugin: In the case of SaaS or local web applications, browser add-ons can be configured to mask data fields corresponding to precise CSS Selectors.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] This can either be accomplished by marking sensitive fields in the application, for example by a HTML class or by finding the right selectors that identify the fields to be obfuscated or masked.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] In latest years, organizations develop their new applications in the cloud more and more often, regardless of whether final applications will be hosted in the cloud or on- premises.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] The cloud solutions as of now allow organizations to use infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and software as a service.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] There are various modes of creating test data and moving it from on-premises databases to the cloud, or between different environments within the cloud.
[src:data-anonymization/data-masking] Dynamic Data Masking becomes even more critical in cloud when customers need to protecting PII data while relying on cloud providers to administer their databases.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Data integrity is a high-priority concern in writing, reading, storage, transmission, or processing of data in computer operating systems and in computer storage and data transmission systems.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] However, only a few of the currently existing and used file systems provide sufficient protection against data corruption.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] To address this issue, data scrubbing provides routine checks of all inconsistencies in data and, in general, prevention of hardware or software failure.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] This "scrubbing" feature occurs commonly in memory, disk arrays, file systems, or FPGAs as a mechanism of error detection and correction.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] With data scrubbing, a RAID controller may periodically read all hard disk drives in a RAID array and check for defective blocks before applications might actually access them.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] This reduces the probability of silent data corruption and data loss due to bit-level errors.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] In Dell PowerEdge RAID environments, a feature called "patrol read" can perform data scrubbing and preventive maintenance.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] In FreeBSD and DragonFly BSD, patrol can be controlled through a RAID controller-specific utility `mfiutil(8)` since FreeBSD 8.0 (2009) and 7.3 (2010).
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] The implementation from FreeBSD was used by the OpenBSD developers for adding patrol support to their generic bio(4) framework and the bioctl utility, without a need for a separate controller-specific utility.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Linux MD RAID, as a software RAID implementation, makes data consistency checks available and provides automated repairing of detected data inconsistencies.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Such procedures are usually performed by setting up a weekly cron job.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Maintenance is performed by issuing operations *check*, *repair*, or *idle* to each of the examined MD devices.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Statuses of all performed operations, as well as general RAID statuses, are always available.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] As a copy-on-write (CoW) file system for Linux, Btrfs provides fault isolation, corruption detection and correction, and file-system scrubbing.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] If the file system detects a checksum mismatch while reading a block, it first tries to obtain (or create) a good copy of this block from another device – if its internal mirroring or RAID techniques are in use.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Btrfs can initiate an online check of the entire file system by triggering a file system scrub job that is performed in the background.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] The scrub job scans the entire file system for integrity and automatically attempts to report and repair any bad blocks it finds along the way.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Files that should not be scrubbed can be marked with the FILE_ATTRIBUTE_NO_SCRUB_DATA flag.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] The features of ZFS, which is a combined file system and logical volume manager, include the verification against data corruption modes, continuous integrity checking, and automatic repair.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Sun Microsystems designed ZFS from the ground up with a focus on data integrity and to protect the data on disks against issues such as disk firmware bugs and phantom writes (a write that never actually makes it to disk).
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] ZFS provides a repair utility called `scrub` that examines and repairs silent data corruption caused by data rot and other problems.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Due to the high integration density of contemporary computer memory chips, the individual memory cell structures became small enough to be vulnerable to cosmic rays and/or alpha particle emission.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] The errors caused by these phenomena are called soft errors.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] This can be a problem for DRAM- and SRAM-based memories.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] Numerous approaches can be taken with respect to scrubbing, from simply reprogramming the FPGA to partial reconfiguration.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] The simplest method of scrubbing is to completely reprogram the FPGA at some periodic rate (typically 1/10 the calculated upset rate).
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] However, the FPGA is not operational during that reprogram time, on the order of micro to milliseconds.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] For situations that cannot tolerate that type of interruption, partial reconfiguration is available.
[src:data-anonymization/data-scrubbing] This technique allows the FPGA to be reprogrammed while still operational.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] When applied to metadata or general data about identification, the process is also known as data anonymization.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Common strategies include deleting or masking personal identifiers, such as personal name, and suppressing or generalizing quasi-identifiers, such as date of birth.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] The reverse process of using de-identified data to identify individuals is known as data re-identification.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Successful re-identifications cast doubt on de-identification's effectiveness.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] A systematic review of fourteen distinct re-identification attacks found "a high re-identification rate […] dominated by small-scale studies on data that was not de-identified according to existing standards".
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] De-identification is adopted as one of the main approaches toward data privacy protection.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] It is commonly used in fields of communications, multimedia, biometrics, big data, cloud computing, data mining, internet, social networks, and audio–video surveillance.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] When surveys are conducted, such as a census, they collect information about a specific group of people.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] To encourage participation and to protect the privacy of survey respondents, the researchers attempt to design the survey in a way that when people participate in a survey, it will not be possible to match any participant's individual response(s) with any data published.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] When an online shopping website wants to know its users' preferences and shopping habits, it decides to retrieve customers' data from its database and do analysis on them.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] The personal data information include personal identifiers which were collected directly when customers created their accounts.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] The website needs to pre-handle the data through de-identification techniques before analyzing data records to avoid violating their customers' privacy.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Anonymization refers to irreversibly severing a data set from the identity of the data contributor in a study to prevent any future re-identification, even by the study organizers under any condition.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] De-identification may also include preserving identifying information which can only be re-linked by a trusted party in certain situations.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] There is a debate in the technology community on whether data that can be re-linked, even by a trusted party, should ever be considered de-identified.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Common strategies of de-identification are masking personal identifiers and generalizing quasi-identifiers.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Pseudonymization is the main technique used to mask personal identifiers from data records, and k-anonymization is usually adopted for generalizing quasi-identifiers.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Pseudonymization is performed by replacing real names with a temporary ID.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] It deletes or masks personal identifiers to make individuals unidentified.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] This method makes it possible to track the individual's record over time, even though the record will be updated.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] However, it can not prevent the individual from being identified if some specific combinations of attributes in the data record indirectly identify the individual.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] k-anonymization defines attributes that indirectly points to the individual's identity as quasi-identifiers (QIs) and deal with data by making at least *k* individuals have some combination of QI values.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] QI values are handled following specific standards.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] For example, the k-anonymization replaces some original data in the records with new range values and keep some values unchanged.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] New combination of QI values prevents the individual from being identified and also avoid destroying data records.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Research into de-identification is driven mostly for protecting health information.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Some libraries have adopted methods used in the healthcare industry to preserve their readers' privacy.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] In big data, de-identification is widely adopted by individuals and organizations.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] With the development of social media, e-commerce, and big data, de-identification is sometimes required and often used for data privacy when users' personal data are collected by companies or third-party organizations who will analyze it for their own personal usage.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] In smart cities, de-identification may be required to protect the privacy of residents, workers and visitors.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Without strict regulation, de-identification may be difficult because sensors can still collect information without consent.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Whenever a person participates in genetics research, the donation of a biological specimen often results in the creation of a large amount of personalized data.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Such data is uniquely difficult to de-identify.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Anonymization of genetic data is particularly difficult because of the huge amount of genotypic information in biospecimens, the ties that specimens often have to medical history, and the advent of modern bioinformatics tools for data mining.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] There have been demonstrations that data for individuals in aggregate collections of genotypic data sets can be tied to the identities of the specimen donors.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Some researchers have suggested that it is not reasonable to ever promise participants in genetics research that they can retain their anonymity, but instead, such participants should be taught the limits of using coded identifiers in a de-identification process.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] In May 2014, the United States President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology found de-identification "somewhat useful as an added safeguard" but not "a useful basis for policy" as "it is not robust against near‐term future re‐identification methods".
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] The HIPAA Privacy Rule provides mechanisms for using and disclosing health data responsibly without the need for patient consent.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] These mechanisms center on two HIPAA de-identification standards – Safe Harbor and the Expert Determination Method.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] That the Covered Entity or Business Associate does not have actual knowledge that the residual information in the data could be used alone, or in combination with other information, to identify an individual.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Safe Harbor is a highly prescriptive approach to de-identification.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Under this method, all dates must be generalized to year and zip codes reduced to three digits.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] The same approach is used on the data regardless of the context.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Even if the information is to be shared with a trusted researcher who wishes to analyze the data for seasonal variations in acute respiratory cases and, thus, requires the month of hospital admission, this information cannot be provided; only the year of admission would be retained.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Expert Determination takes a risk-based approach to de-identification that applies current standards and best practices from the research to determine the likelihood that a person could be identified from their protected health information.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] This method requires that a person with appropriate knowledge of and experience with generally accepted statistical and scientific principles and methods render the information not individually identifiable.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] Documents the methods and results of the analysis that justify such a determination.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] The key law about research in electronic health record data is HIPAA Privacy Rule.
[src:data-anonymization/de-identification] This law allows use of electronic health record of deceased subjects for research (HIPAA Privacy Rule (section 164.512(i)(1)(iii))).
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization (or pseudonymisation, the spelling under European guidelines) is one way to comply with the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) demands for secure data storage of personal information.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data can be restored to its original state with the addition of information which allows individuals to be re-identified.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] In contrast, anonymization is intended to prevent re-identification of individuals within the dataset.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] The European Data Protection Supervisor (EDPS) on 9 December 2021 highlighted pseudonymization as the top technical supplementary measure for Schrems II compliance.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Less than two weeks later, the EU Commission highlighted pseudonymization as an essential element of the equivalency decision for South Korea, which is the status that was lost by the United States under the Schrems II ruling by the Court of Justice of the European Union (CJEU).
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Protects against unauthorized re-identification via the mosaic effect by generating high entropy (uncertainty) levels by dynamically assigning different tokens at different times for various purposes.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Before the Schrems II ruling, pseudonymization was a technique used by security experts or government officials to hide personally identifiable information to maintain data structure and privacy of information.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Some common examples of sensitive information include postal code, location of individuals, names of individuals, race and gender, etc.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] After the Schrems II ruling, GDPR-compliant pseudonymization must satisfy the above-noted elements as an "outcome" versus merely a technique.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] The choice of which data fields are to be pseudonymized is partly subjective.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Less selective fields, such as birth date or postal code are often also included because they are usually available from other sources and therefore make a record easier to identify.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymizing these less identifying fields removes most of their analytic value and is therefore normally accompanied by the introduction of new derived and less identifying forms, such as year of birth or a larger postal code region.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Data fields that are less identifying, such as date of attendance, are usually not pseudonymized.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] This is because too much statistical utility is lost in doing so, not because the data cannot be identified.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] For example, given prior knowledge of a few attendance dates it is easy to identify someone's data in a pseudonymized dataset by selecting only those people with that pattern of dates.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] This is an example of an inference attack.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] The weakness of pre-GDPR pseudonymized data to inference attacks is commonly overlooked.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] A famous example is the AOL search data scandal.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] The pseudonym allows tracking back of data to its origins, which distinguishes pseudonymization from anonymization, where all person-related data that could allow backtracking has been purged.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization is an issue in, for example, patient-related data that has to be passed on securely between clinical centers.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] The application of pseudonymization to e-health intends to preserve the patient's privacy and data confidentiality.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] It allows primary use of medical records by authorized health care providers and privacy preserving secondary use by researchers.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] In the US, HIPAA provides guidelines on how health care data must be handled and data de-identification or pseudonymization is one way to simplify HIPAA compliance.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] However, plain pseudonymization for privacy preservation often reaches its limits when genetic data are involved (see also genetic privacy).
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Due to the identifying nature of genetic data, depersonalization is often not sufficient to hide the corresponding person.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Potential solutions are the combination of pseudonymization with fragmentation and encryption.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Effective as of May 25, 2018, the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) defines pseudonymization for the very first time at the EU level in Article 4(5).
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Under Article 4(5) definitional requirements, data is pseudonymized if it cannot be attributed to a specific data subject without the use of separately kept "additional information".
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymized data embodies the state of the art in Data Protection by Design and by Default because it requires protection of both direct and indirect identifiers (not just direct).
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Because access to separately kept "additional information" is required for re-identification, attribution of data to a specific data subject can be limited by the controller to support lawful purposes only.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] "...implement appropriate technical and organizational measures for ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] That obligation applies to the amount of personal data collected, the extent of their processing, the period of their storage and their accessibility.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] A central core of Data Protection by Design and by Default under GDPR Article 25 is enforcement of technology controls that support appropriate uses and the ability to keep promises.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] This trust cannot be maintained using outdated approaches to data protection.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Pseudonymization, as newly defined under the GDPR, is a means of helping to achieve Data Protection by Design and by Default to earn and maintain trust and more effectively serve businesses, researchers, healthcare providers, and everyone who relies on the integrity of data.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] GDPR-compliant pseudonymization not only enables greater privacy-respectful use of data in the "big data" world of data sharing and combining, but it also enables data controllers and processors to reap explicit benefits under the GDPR for correctly pseudonymized data.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Article 9(2)(j) with regard to overcoming the general prohibition on processing Article 9(1) special categories of personal data.
[src:data-anonymization/pseudonymization] Under Article 20(1), data controllers using Legitimate Interest processing are not subject to the right of portability, which applies only to consent-based processing.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Data generated by a computer simulation can be seen as synthetic data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This encompasses most applications of physical modeling, such as music synthesizers or flight simulators.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] The output of such systems approximates the real thing, but is fully algorithmically generated.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Synthetic data is used in a variety of fields as a filter for information that would otherwise compromise the confidentiality of particular aspects of the data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In many sensitive applications, datasets theoretically exist but cannot be released to the general public; synthetic data sidesteps the privacy issues that arise from using real consumer information without permission or compensation.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Synthetic data is generated to meet specific needs or certain conditions that may not be found in the original, real data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] One of the hurdles in applying up-to-date machine learning approaches for complex scientific tasks is the scarcity of labeled data, a gap effectively bridged by the use of synthetic data, which closely replicates real experimental data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This can be useful when designing many systems, from simulations based on theoretical value, to database processors, etc.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This helps detect and solve unexpected issues such as information processing limitations.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Synthetic data are often generated to represent the authentic data and allows a baseline to be set.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Another benefit of synthetic data is to protect the privacy and confidentiality of authentic data, while still allowing for use in testing systems.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Computer security experts claim generated synthetic data "... enables us to create realistic behavior profiles for users and attackers.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] At the same time, synthetic data together with the testing approach can give the ability to model real-world scenarios.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Scientific modelling of physical systems has a long history that runs concurrent with the history of physics.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] For example, research into synthesis of audio and voice can be traced back to the 1930s and before, driven forward by the developments of the telephone and audio recording technologies.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Digitization gave rise to software synthesizers from the 1970s onwards.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In the context of privacy-preserving statistical analysis, in 1993, the idea of original fully synthetic data was created by Donald Rubin.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Rubin originally designed this to synthesize the Decennial Census long form responses for the short form households.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] He then released samples that did not include any actual long form records - in this he preserved anonymity of the household.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Later that year, the idea of original partially synthetic data was created by Little.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Little used this idea to synthesize the sensitive values on the public use file.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] A 1993 work fitted a statistical model to 60,000 MNIST digits, then it was used to generate over 1 million examples.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Those were used to train a LeNet-4 to reach state of the art performance.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In 1994, Stephen Fienberg introduced 'critical refinement', in which a parametric posterior predictive distribution (instead of a Bayes bootstrap) is used to do the sampling.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Later, other important contributors to the development of synthetic data generation were Trivellore Raghunathan, Jerry Reiter, Donald Rubin, John M.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Collectively they came up with a solution for how to treat partially synthetic data with missing data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Similarly, they developed the technique of Sequential Regression Multivariate Imputation.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Researchers test the framework on synthetic data, which is "the only source of ground truth on which they can objectively assess the performance of their algorithms".
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Synthetic data can be generated through the use of random lines, having different orientations and starting positions.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] A more complicated dataset can be generated by using a synthesizer build.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] To create a synthesizer build, first use the original data to create a model or equation that fits the data the best.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This model or equation will be called a synthesizer build.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This build can be used to generate more data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Constructing a synthesizer build involves constructing a statistical model.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In a linear regression line example, the original data can be plotted, and a best fit linear line can be created from the data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This line is a synthesizer created from the original data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] The next step will be generating more synthetic data from the synthesizer build or from this linear line equation.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In this way, the new data can be used for studies and research, and it protects the confidentiality of the original data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Generate attribute values based on user-supplied prior probabilities.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Since the attribute values of one object may depend on the attribute values of related objects, the attribute generation process assigns values collectively.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Testing and training fraud detection and confidentiality systems are devised using synthetic data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Specific algorithms and generators are designed to create realistic data, which then assists in teaching a system how to react to certain situations or criteria.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] For example, intrusion detection software is tested using synthetic data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This data is a representation of the authentic data and may include intrusion instances that are not found in the authentic data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] The synthetic data allows the software to recognize these situations and react accordingly.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] If synthetic data was not used, the software would only be trained to react to the situations provided by the authentic data and it may not recognize another type of intrusion.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Researchers doing clinical trials or any other research may generate synthetic data to aid in creating a baseline for future studies and testing.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Real data can contain information that researchers may not want released, so synthetic data is sometimes used to protect the privacy and confidentiality of a dataset.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Using synthetic data reduces confidentiality and privacy issues since it holds no personal information and cannot be traced back to any individual.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Beyond privacy protection, synthetic data is also being explored for methodological innovation in drug development.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] For instance, synthetic data may be used to construct synthetic control arms as an alternative to conventional external control arms based on real-world data (RWD) or randomized controlled trials (RCTs).
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Collectively, regulatory agencies such as the FDA and EMA appear to be at various stages of recognizing and integrating AI-generated synthetic data into their methodologies.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] The quality and statistical handling of synthetic data are expected to become more prominent in future regulatory discussions, particularly in contexts such as predictive modeling (e.g., digital twins), where innovative approaches have already been referenced.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Synthetic data is increasingly being used for machine learning applications: a model is trained on a synthetically generated dataset with the intention of transfer learning to real data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Efforts have been made to enable more data science experiments via the construction of general-purpose synthetic data generators, such as the Synthetic Data Vault.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] This usage of synthetic data has been proposed for computer vision applications, in particular object detection, where the synthetic environment is a 3D model of the object, and learning to navigate environments by visual information.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In the context of large language model training, synthetic data generation has become a core component of the post-training pipeline.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] At the same time, transfer learning remains a nontrivial problem, and synthetic data has not become ubiquitous yet.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Research results indicate that adding a small amount of real data significantly improves transfer learning with synthetic data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Advances in generative adversarial networks (GAN), lead to the natural idea that one can produce data and then use it for training.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] Since at least 2016, such adversarial training has been successfully used to produce synthetic data of sufficient quality to produce state-of-the-art results in some domains, without even needing to re-mix real data in with the generated synthetic data.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In 1987, a Navlab autonomous vehicle used 1200 synthetic road images as one approach to training.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In 2021, Microsoft released a database of 100,000 synthetic faces based on (500 real faces) that claims to "match real data in accuracy".
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] In 2023, Nature (journal) published a cover of their Nature's 10 series designed by Kim Albrecht of the project "Artificial Worldviews." The cover features a mapping of over 18,000 synthetically generated data points prompted from ChatGPT on the categories of knowledge.
[src:data-anonymization/synthetic-data] DataFramer has published datasets on Hugging Face, including *ehr-multi-file-patient-samples*, a synthetic multi-file patient history dataset, and *INSURE-Dial*, a dialogue dataset for insurance-call phase detection and compliance verification.
